{"title_page": "Jo Weldon", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jo Weldon\n| image       = Jo_Weldon_at_Miss_Exotic_World_2009_(crop).jpg\n| alt         = Jo Weldon at Miss Exotic World Pageant in 2009\n| caption     = Weldon in 2009\n| imagesize   = 200px\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date  = 1962<!--{{Birth date and age|1985|5|16}} Unknown, please add (with reliable source)-->\n| birth_place = <!--New York City Unknown, please add (with reliable source)-->\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American\n| occupation  = [[Burlesque]] performer, author, photographer,\n| known_for   = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| spouse      = \n| website     = {{URL|schoolofburlesque.com}}\n| children    =\n}}\n'''Jo Weldon''' (born 1962),<ref>{{cite news|title=Dressed to Kill: The Power of Leopard Prints|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/29/arts/design/dressed-to-kill-the-power-ofleopard-prints.html|last=Kahn|first=Eve M.|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=February 5, 2017|archivedate=February 23, 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190223000241/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/29/arts/design/dressed-to-kill-the-power-ofleopard-prints.html|url-status=live|quote=...the year of her birth (1962...}}</ref> commonly known as '''Jo Boobs''' or '''Jo Boobs Weldon''', is a performer, author, activist, and educator based in New York City. Weldon's body of work centers around stripping and [[striptease]]. She established and runs [[The New York School of Burlesque]] and wrote ''The Burlesque Handbook''.<ref>Lewis, Steve. [http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 My Intimate Interview with Burlesque Queen Jo Boobs Weldon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213446/http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 |date=October 4, 2013 }}, BlackBook, November 4, 2011. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> She is an advocate for sex-worker rights and freedom of sexual expression.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first= Holli-Mae|url=http://21stcenturyburlesque.com/burlycon-past-present-and-future/ |title=BurlyCon \u2013 Past, Present and Future|publisher= 21st Century Burlesque|date= September 13, 2011|accessdate= March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2019}}\nAfter moving to New York in 1997, Weldon took part in burlesque shows at The Blue Angel and Coney Island and was inspired by performances from [[Angie Pontani]], Bambi the Mermaid and Remy Vicious.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} Weldon's academic career includes a degree in Business Administration, with her graduate work in media ethics. During her internships, she worked writing summaries of [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] activities and writing scripts for [[CNN]].\n\n==Burlesque==\n[[File:Jo Boobs (562826292).jpg|thumb|left|Weldon performing at [[Miss Exotic World Pageant]] in 2007]]\nWeldon's burlesque style spans classical burlesque to [[Avant-garde|avant garde]] performance art. In her signature [[Godzilla]] act she strips from a monster costume to a mashup of [[Blue \u00d6yster Cult]]'s song \"[[Godzilla (Blue \u00d6yster Cult song)|Godzilla]]\" and sound clips from the [[Gojira (1954)|original Godzilla movie]]. Weldon describes herself as \"an [[Absurdism|absurdist]] and a [[Surrealism|surrealist]] as well as a lover of glamour.\"<ref>Weldon in {{cite web|url=http://javasbachelorpad.com/joboobs.html|title= Jo Boobs|publisher= Java's Bachelor Pad|date= July 2006|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=February 24, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170224121052/http://javasbachelorpad.com/joboobs.html|url-status=live}}</ref> She has performed internationally and in unusual venues such as the [[New York Public Library]], where she performed a tribute to [[Gypsy Rose Lee]] as part of the Gypsy Centennial celebration.<ref>[http://www.bust.com/artsy/here-she-is-world-celebrate-gypsy-s-100th-birthday-with-the-new-york-public-library.html \"Here she is, world!\" Celebrate Gypsy's 100th Birthday with The New York Public Library], Bust Magazine. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref>\n\nWeldon is co-executive director of education at the [[Burlesque Hall of Fame]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], Nevada. She has judged and coordinated judging for the Hall's [[Miss Exotic World Pageant]]. In 2012 she was awarded the Sassy Lassy Award for Recognition of Outstanding Contribution to the Art of Burlesque.<ref>{{cite web|last=Droganes|first=Constance|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/burlesque-diva-jo-weldon-wants-you-to-take-it-off-1.520218 |title=Burlesque diva Jo Weldon wants you to take it off|publisher=[[CTV News]]| date= June 8, 2010| accessdate= March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWeldon was inspired by the sideshows and burlesque shows of [[Coney Island]] in the mid-1990s, and has moderated the Wild Women Panel, among others, as part of Coney Island's annual Congress of Curious People.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mixson|first=Colin|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/2012/15/24_boobzilla_2012_04_13_bk.html?from=bd| title= Weird sisters: Sideshow women talk feminism in Coney|work=[[Brooklyn Paper]]|date= April 16, 2012|accessdate=  March 30, 2013|archivedate= February 22, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190222235312/https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/2012/15/24_boobzilla_2012_04_13_bk.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Weldon has produced shows for Coney Island's Burlesque at the Beach series, including her annual Follies Fromage, a show based entirely on cheese, and the autobiographical ''God-Damned Women'' show. She is the coordinator and lead instructor of the Coney Island University Master Class in Burlesque.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coneyislanduniversity.com/ |publisher=Coney Island University |title=Sono Varieta|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching and The New York School of Burlesque==\n[[File:Jo Weldon at Burlesque Hall of Fame 2010-02.jpg|thumb|165px|Weldon performing at [[Burlesque Hall of Fame|BHF]] in 2010.]]\nWeldon is an educator and authority on the topic of burlesque.<ref>[http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/35589/Jo_Weldon/index.aspx Author Jo Weldon], Harper Collins Publishers Retrieved on March 30, 2013.</ref> She is the founder, in 2003, and headmistress of [[The New York School of Burlesque]]. The school has taught disabled performers at [[DaDaFest]] in Liverpool, UK, and taught breast cancer survivors through its Pink Light Burlesque program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ravenous.journurl.com/2011/05/03/presenting-jo-weldon-rim-shot-please/|title=Presenting Jo Weldon! (Rim shot, please!)]|publisher=Ravenous.Journal.com|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=April 11, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130411050616/http://ravenous.journurl.com/2011/05/03/presenting-jo-weldon-rim-shot-please/|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWeldon is the founder of Pink Light Burlesque, an organization to provide burlesque classes free of cost to breast cancer patients and survivors.<ref>[http://www.pinklightburlesque.com/ Pink Light Burlesque] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203115632/http://www.pinklightburlesque.com/ |date=December 3, 2011}}, Official website. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> The first Pink Light Burlesque showcase in December 2011 was featured in TIME.<ref>Santa Cruz, Lauren. [http://healthland.time.com/2012/01/26/pink-light-burlesque-breast-cancer-survivors-strip-down-and-celebrate/ Pink Light Burlesque: Breast Cancer Survivors Strip Down and Celebrate], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', January 26, 2012. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> Pink Light Burlesque classes have beeb held in Seattle, New York and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shadwell|first=Talia|url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/8269167/Burlesque-a-confidence-boost-for-cancer-survivors |title=Burlesque a confidence boost for cancer survivors|series=[[Manawatu Standard]]|location=Palmerstown North, New Zealand|work=[[Stuff (company)|Stuff]]|date= February 3, 2013|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=February 8, 2013|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130208053718/http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/8269167/Burlesque-a-confidence-boost-for-cancer-survivors|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n===''The Burlesque Handbook''===\n\nWeldon is author ''The Burlesque Handbook'' (HarperCollins/ItBooks 2010), which developed from a compilation of her class handouts and from a 50-page ebook that she had already produced covering technique and performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Devotchka|first= Divertida|url= http://pincurlmag.com/jo-weldon |title=Jo Weldon|work= Pin Curl|date= October 31, 2010|accessdate= March 30, 2013| archivedate= June 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627010713/http://pincurlmag.com/jo-weldon|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has a foreword by comedian [[Margaret Cho]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Lewsis| url=http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 |title=My Intimate Interview with Burlesque Queen Jo Boobs Weldon|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213446/http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 |archivedate=October 4, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Jo Weldon behind the camera.jpg|thumb|left|Weldon taking photos at Miss Exotic World (2007).]]\n\n===Blogging===\nFrom 2001 to 2010, Weldon produced the website G-Strings Forever, a collection of photographs and articles about stripping and burlesque.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.gstringsforever.com Internet Archive for http://www.gstringsforever.com], Wayback Machine. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> She maintained a [[LiveJournal]] account from 2004 to 2010 where she wrote extensively on burlesque, sex work, and women's issues.<ref>Weldon, Jo. [http://gstringgirl.livejournal.com/ Eau de Jo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309234522/http://gstringgirl.livejournal.com/ |date=March 9, 2013 }}, [[LiveJournal]], December 22, 2011. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> Since 2007 Weldon has written the burlesque blog Burlesque Daily. From 2010 to 2011, Weldon answered burlesque questions on her [[Spring.me|Formspring]] account.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weldon|first=Jo|url=http://www.formspring.me/schoolofburlesq|title=Ask me anything about Burlesque!|publisher=[[Spring.me|Formspring]]|date=May 24, 2011|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=April 12, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130412185651/http://www.formspring.me/schoolofburlesq|url-status=live}}</ref> She writes a burlesque etiquette column for Pin Curl Magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weldon|first= Jo|url=http://pincurlmag.com/backstage-etiquette-with-jo-boobs |title=Backstage Etiquette with Jo Boobs|work= Pin Curl|date= March 31, 2012|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=January 4, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104222738/http://pincurlmag.com/backstage-etiquette-with-jo-boobs|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nWeldon publishes essays and articles on the topics of stripping, sex-worker rights, burlesque history, and burlesque performance. She has consulted for, and was profiled in two webisodes of, the movie ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]''.<ref>[http://www.christinaaguilera.com/us/news/show-me-how-you-burlesque-episode-1 Show me how you burlesque \u2013 episode 1], Christina Aguilera official website, December 8, 2010. Retrieved March 20, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.christinaaguilera.com/us/news/show-me-how-you-burlesque-episode-2 Show me how you burlesque \u2013 episode 2], Christina Aguilera official website, December 22, 2010. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Sex-work advocacy==\nWeldon supports and works for the rights of strippers and other [[sex workers]]. She has attended and spoken at academic conferences, including the 1999 Socialist Scholar's Conference,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ditmore|first= Melissa Hope|title=Prostitution and Sex Work |publisher= Greenwood|year= 2011|page='''??'''}}</ref> the American Philosophical Association Pacific Division Meeting, the International Congress on Prostitution, and the United Nations Beijing Plus Five Conference, where she lobbied for the adoption of the term \"sex work\" and for a distinction between forced and voluntary sex work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nerve.com//content/a-lifes-work-the-strippers-advocate |title=A Life's Work: The Stripper's Advocate|publisher= Nerve.com |accessdate= March 30, 2013|date=May 12, 2004|archivedate=December 16, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091216061301/http://www.nerve.com/regulars/lifeswork/strippersadvocate/}}</ref> Weldon has written articles on sex work and sex worker rights.<ref>{{cite web|last= Weldon|first= Jo|url=http://www.thescavenger.net/feminism-a-pop-culture/sex-work-research-needs-to-focus-on-money-93786-350.html |title=Sex work research needs to focus on money|publisher=TheScavenger.net|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=May 12, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170512091418/http://thescavenger.net/feminism-a-pop-culture-sp-9560/feminism-a-pop-culture/350-sex-work-research-needs-to-focus-on-money-93786.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Weldon also toured with the Sex Worker Arts Show,<ref>{{cite news|last=Huang|first=Karen|url= http://fnewsmagazine.com/2007-feb/sex-as-work.php |title=Sex as Work|work= F News|date= February 2007|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=September 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140901114959/http://fnewsmagazine.com/2007-feb/sex-as-work.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sexworkersartshow.com/bios_jo_03152009.html |title=Jo Weldon| publisher= Sex Worker Arts Show|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=November 28, 2009|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091128090516/http://www.sexworkersartshow.com/bios_jo_03152009.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and co-produced ''W.O.(e).R.D., Women of experience Read Downtown'', a performance reading of literary works by undomesticated women.<ref>{{cite web|last= Ikard|first= Theresa|url=http://carnalnation.com/content/51279/5/jo-weldon |title=Burlesque's Jo Weldon on Feminism, Fluid Sexuality, Domestication Drag|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101120225134/http://carnalnation.com/content/51279/5/jo-weldon |archivedate=November 20, 2010|publisher=Carnal Nation|date=April 3, 2010|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Television and film appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" cellpadding=\"3\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"70\" | Year !! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" width=\"280\" | Appearance !! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" width=\"100\" | Role !! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" width=\"300\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1999 || Time Square Clean-Up || Herself || TV, Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1999\u20132006 || ''[[SexTV]]'' || Herself || TV series documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2005 || ''[[Leonard Cohen: I'm Your Man]]'' || Burlesque Beauty || Documentary, biography\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2006 || Monja satanica || Estudiante Amore || Short horror\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2006 || [[Josh Alan Friedman|''Tales of Times Square'']] || Anna Turner|| Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2006 || Alison Lapper/Spread Magazine/Lust Circus || Herself || TV, Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2007 || [[What Not to Wear (U.S. TV series)|''What Not to Wear'']] || Herself || TV, Reality\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2008, 2009 || ''[[Gossip Girl]]'' ||   || TV, Drama, Romance\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2009 || No Strings Attached || Herself \u2013 Jo Boobs || Short\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2010 || Dirty Martini and the New Burlesque || Herself \u2013 Jo Boobs || Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2010 || ''[[The Real Housewives of New York City]]'' || Herself || TV, Reality\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2011 || Show Me How You Burlesque || Herself || Webisodes, Documentary\n|-|\n|}\n\n==Books, essays and DVDs==\n\n'''Essays'''\n* Editors: Brewer, Gwen; Bullough, Vern L; Douglas, Jeffrey J; Elias, James E, Elias, Veronica Diehl. ''Porn 101: Eroticism Pornography and the First Amendment'' (Prometheus Books, 1999) Collection of essays including: Weldon, Jo. ''Topping from Below: Does Female Dominant Pornography Endorse the Rape of Women?''\n* Editors: Egan, Danielle; Frank, Katherine; Johnson, Merri Lisa. ''Flesh for Fantasy: Producing and Consuming Exotic Dance'' (Seal Press 2004) Collection of essays including: Weldon, Jo. ''Whipped Cream, Fire Eating, and the Other Delights of Feature Dancing''\n* Editors: Kramer Bussel, Rachel; Tyler, Alison. ''Hide and Seek: Erotic Tales of Voyeurs and Exhibitionists'' (Cleis Press, 2010) Weldon, Jo. ''Forward: Opening Doors''\n\n'''DVDs'''\n* Director: Weldon, Jo. Featuring: Weldon, Jo. ''Honey and Spice: Sensual and Fierce Burlesque'' Studio: [[World Dance New York]] (2009) DVD / instant video\n* Director: Weldon, Jo. Featuring: Weldon, Jo. ''Silk and Feathers: Burlesque Fan Dance'' Studio: [[World Dance New York]] (2009) DVD / instant video\n* Director: Weldon, Jo. Featuring: Weldon, Jo. ''Striptease for Burlesque, Exotic Dance & Every Day'' Studio: [[World Dance New York]] (2009) DVD / instant video\n\n'''Books'''\n\n* Weldon, Jo. ''The Burlesque Handbook'' (It Books, 2010)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jo Weldon}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n*{{cite news|last=Gasten|first= David|url=http://thethingis.co.uk/2010/11/29/the-burlesque-show-is-almost-over/ | title=Why The Burlesque Show Is Over|work= The Thing Is|date= November 29, 2010|accessdate= March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weldon, Jo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Neo-Burlesque performers]]\n[[Category:American female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American vedettes]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jo Weldon\n| image       = Jo_Weldon_at_Miss_Exotic_World_2009_(crop).jpg\n| alt         = Jo Weldon at Miss Exotic World Pageant in 2009\n| caption     = Weldon in 2009\n| imagesize   = 200px\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date  = 1962<!--{{Birth date and age|1985|5|16}} Unknown, please add (with reliable source)-->\n| birth_place = <!--New York City Unknown, please add (with reliable source)-->\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American\n| occupation  = [[Burlesque]] performer, author, photographer,\n| known_for   = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| spouse      = \n| website     = {{URL|schoolofburlesque.com}}\n| children    =\n}}\n'''Jo Weldon''' (born 1962),<ref>{{cite news|title=Dressed to Kill: The Power of Leopard Prints|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/29/arts/design/dressed-to-kill-the-power-ofleopard-prints.html|last=Kahn|first=Eve M.|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 28, 2016|accessdate=February 5, 2017|archivedate=February 23, 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190223000241/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/29/arts/design/dressed-to-kill-the-power-ofleopard-prints.html|url-status=live|quote=...the year of her birth (1962...}}</ref> commonly known as '''Jo Boobs''' or '''Jo Boobs Weldon''', is a performer, author, activist, and educator based in New York City. Weldon's body of work centers around stripping and [[striptease]]. She established and runs [[The New York School of Burlesque]] and wrote ''The Burlesque Handbook''.<ref>Lewis, Steve. [http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 My Intimate Interview with Burlesque Queen Jo Boobs Weldon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213446/http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 |date=October 4, 2013 }}, BlackBook, November 4, 2011. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> She is an advocate for sex-worker rights and freedom of sexual expression.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first= Holli-Mae|url=http://21stcenturyburlesque.com/burlycon-past-present-and-future/ |title=BurlyCon \u2013 Past, Present and Future|publisher= 21st Century Burlesque|date= September 13, 2011|accessdate= March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2019}}\nAfter moving to New York in 1997, Weldon took part in burlesque shows at The Blue Angel and Coney Island and was inspired by performances from [[Angie Pontani]], Bambi the Mermaid and Remy Vicious.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} Weldon's academic career includes a degree in Business Administration, with her graduate work in media ethics. During her internships, she worked writing summaries of [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] activities and writing scripts for [[CNN]].\n\n==Burlesque==\n[[File:Jo Boobs (562826292).jpg|thumb|left|Weldon performing at [[Miss Exotic World Pageant]] in 2007]]\nWeldon's burlesque style spans classical burlesque to [[Avant-garde|avant garde]] performance art. In her signature [[Godzilla]] act she strips from a monster costume to a mashup of [[Blue \u00d6yster Cult]]'s song \"[[Godzilla (song)|Godzilla]]\" and sound clips from the [[Gojira (1954)|original Godzilla movie]]. Weldon describes herself as \"an [[Absurdism|absurdist]] and a [[Surrealism|surrealist]] as well as a lover of glamour.\"<ref>Weldon in {{cite web|url=http://javasbachelorpad.com/joboobs.html|title= Jo Boobs|publisher= Java's Bachelor Pad|date= July 2006|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=February 24, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170224121052/http://javasbachelorpad.com/joboobs.html|url-status=live}}</ref> She has performed internationally and in unusual venues such as the [[New York Public Library]], where she performed a tribute to [[Gypsy Rose Lee]] as part of the Gypsy Centennial celebration.<ref>[http://www.bust.com/artsy/here-she-is-world-celebrate-gypsy-s-100th-birthday-with-the-new-york-public-library.html \"Here she is, world!\" Celebrate Gypsy's 100th Birthday with The New York Public Library], Bust Magazine. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref>\n\nWeldon is co-executive director of education at the [[Burlesque Hall of Fame]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], Nevada. She has judged and coordinated judging for the Hall's [[Miss Exotic World Pageant]]. In 2012 she was awarded the Sassy Lassy Award for Recognition of Outstanding Contribution to the Art of Burlesque.<ref>{{cite web|last=Droganes|first=Constance|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/burlesque-diva-jo-weldon-wants-you-to-take-it-off-1.520218 |title=Burlesque diva Jo Weldon wants you to take it off|publisher=[[CTV News]]| date= June 8, 2010| accessdate= March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWeldon was inspired by the sideshows and burlesque shows of [[Coney Island]] in the mid-1990s, and has moderated the Wild Women Panel, among others, as part of Coney Island's annual Congress of Curious People.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mixson|first=Colin|url=https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/2012/15/24_boobzilla_2012_04_13_bk.html?from=bd| title= Weird sisters: Sideshow women talk feminism in Coney|work=[[Brooklyn Paper]]|date= April 16, 2012|accessdate=  March 30, 2013|archivedate= February 22, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190222235312/https://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/2012/15/24_boobzilla_2012_04_13_bk.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Weldon has produced shows for Coney Island's Burlesque at the Beach series, including her annual Follies Fromage, a show based entirely on cheese, and the autobiographical ''God-Damned Women'' show. She is the coordinator and lead instructor of the Coney Island University Master Class in Burlesque.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coneyislanduniversity.com/ |publisher=Coney Island University |title=Sono Varieta|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching and The New York School of Burlesque==\n[[File:Jo Weldon at Burlesque Hall of Fame 2010-02.jpg|thumb|165px|Weldon performing at [[Burlesque Hall of Fame|BHF]] in 2010.]]\nWeldon is an educator and authority on the topic of burlesque.<ref>[http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/35589/Jo_Weldon/index.aspx Author Jo Weldon], Harper Collins Publishers Retrieved on March 30, 2013.</ref> She is the founder, in 2003, and headmistress of [[The New York School of Burlesque]]. The school has taught disabled performers at [[DaDaFest]] in Liverpool, UK, and taught breast cancer survivors through its Pink Light Burlesque program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ravenous.journurl.com/2011/05/03/presenting-jo-weldon-rim-shot-please/|title=Presenting Jo Weldon! (Rim shot, please!)]|publisher=Ravenous.Journal.com|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=April 11, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130411050616/http://ravenous.journurl.com/2011/05/03/presenting-jo-weldon-rim-shot-please/|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWeldon is the founder of Pink Light Burlesque, an organization to provide burlesque classes free of cost to breast cancer patients and survivors.<ref>[http://www.pinklightburlesque.com/ Pink Light Burlesque] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203115632/http://www.pinklightburlesque.com/ |date=December 3, 2011}}, Official website. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> The first Pink Light Burlesque showcase in December 2011 was featured in TIME.<ref>Santa Cruz, Lauren. [http://healthland.time.com/2012/01/26/pink-light-burlesque-breast-cancer-survivors-strip-down-and-celebrate/ Pink Light Burlesque: Breast Cancer Survivors Strip Down and Celebrate], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', January 26, 2012. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> Pink Light Burlesque classes have beeb held in Seattle, New York and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shadwell|first=Talia|url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/8269167/Burlesque-a-confidence-boost-for-cancer-survivors |title=Burlesque a confidence boost for cancer survivors|series=[[Manawatu Standard]]|location=Palmerstown North, New Zealand|work=[[Stuff (company)|Stuff]]|date= February 3, 2013|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=February 8, 2013|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130208053718/http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/8269167/Burlesque-a-confidence-boost-for-cancer-survivors|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n===''The Burlesque Handbook''===\n\nWeldon is author ''The Burlesque Handbook'' (HarperCollins/ItBooks 2010), which developed from a compilation of her class handouts and from a 50-page ebook that she had already produced covering technique and performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Devotchka|first= Divertida|url= http://pincurlmag.com/jo-weldon |title=Jo Weldon|work= Pin Curl|date= October 31, 2010|accessdate= March 30, 2013| archivedate= June 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627010713/http://pincurlmag.com/jo-weldon|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has a foreword by comedian [[Margaret Cho]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Lewsis| url=http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 |title=My Intimate Interview with Burlesque Queen Jo Boobs Weldon|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213446/http://www.blackbookmag.com/good-night-mr-lewis-1.109/my-intimate-interview-with-burlesque-queen-jo-boobs-weldon-1.40830 |archivedate=October 4, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Jo Weldon behind the camera.jpg|thumb|left|Weldon taking photos at Miss Exotic World (2007).]]\n\n===Blogging===\nFrom 2001 to 2010, Weldon produced the website G-Strings Forever, a collection of photographs and articles about stripping and burlesque.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.gstringsforever.com Internet Archive for http://www.gstringsforever.com], Wayback Machine. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> She maintained a [[LiveJournal]] account from 2004 to 2010 where she wrote extensively on burlesque, sex work, and women's issues.<ref>Weldon, Jo. [http://gstringgirl.livejournal.com/ Eau de Jo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309234522/http://gstringgirl.livejournal.com/ |date=March 9, 2013 }}, [[LiveJournal]], December 22, 2011. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref> Since 2007 Weldon has written the burlesque blog Burlesque Daily. From 2010 to 2011, Weldon answered burlesque questions on her [[Spring.me|Formspring]] account.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weldon|first=Jo|url=http://www.formspring.me/schoolofburlesq|title=Ask me anything about Burlesque!|publisher=[[Spring.me|Formspring]]|date=May 24, 2011|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=April 12, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130412185651/http://www.formspring.me/schoolofburlesq|url-status=live}}</ref> She writes a burlesque etiquette column for Pin Curl Magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weldon|first= Jo|url=http://pincurlmag.com/backstage-etiquette-with-jo-boobs |title=Backstage Etiquette with Jo Boobs|work= Pin Curl|date= March 31, 2012|accessdate=March 30, 2013|archivedate=January 4, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104222738/http://pincurlmag.com/backstage-etiquette-with-jo-boobs|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nWeldon publishes essays and articles on the topics of stripping, sex-worker rights, burlesque history, and burlesque performance. She has consulted for, and was profiled in two webisodes of, the movie ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]''.<ref>[http://www.christinaaguilera.com/us/news/show-me-how-you-burlesque-episode-1 Show me how you burlesque \u2013 episode 1], Christina Aguilera official website, December 8, 2010. Retrieved March 20, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.christinaaguilera.com/us/news/show-me-how-you-burlesque-episode-2 Show me how you burlesque \u2013 episode 2], Christina Aguilera official website, December 22, 2010. Retrieved March 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Sex-work advocacy==\nWeldon supports and works for the rights of strippers and other [[sex workers]]. She has attended and spoken at academic conferences, including the 1999 Socialist Scholar's Conference,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ditmore|first= Melissa Hope|title=Prostitution and Sex Work |publisher= Greenwood|year= 2011|page='''??'''}}</ref> the American Philosophical Association Pacific Division Meeting, the International Congress on Prostitution, and the United Nations Beijing Plus Five Conference, where she lobbied for the adoption of the term \"sex work\" and for a distinction between forced and voluntary sex work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nerve.com//content/a-lifes-work-the-strippers-advocate |title=A Life's Work: The Stripper's Advocate|publisher= Nerve.com |accessdate= March 30, 2013|date=May 12, 2004|archivedate=December 16, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091216061301/http://www.nerve.com/regulars/lifeswork/strippersadvocate/}}</ref> Weldon has written articles on sex work and sex worker rights.<ref>{{cite web|last= Weldon|first= Jo|url=http://www.thescavenger.net/feminism-a-pop-culture/sex-work-research-needs-to-focus-on-money-93786-350.html |title=Sex work research needs to focus on money|publisher=TheScavenger.net|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=May 12, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170512091418/http://thescavenger.net/feminism-a-pop-culture-sp-9560/feminism-a-pop-culture/350-sex-work-research-needs-to-focus-on-money-93786.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Weldon also toured with the Sex Worker Arts Show,<ref>{{cite news|last=Huang|first=Karen|url= http://fnewsmagazine.com/2007-feb/sex-as-work.php |title=Sex as Work|work= F News|date= February 2007|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=September 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140901114959/http://fnewsmagazine.com/2007-feb/sex-as-work.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sexworkersartshow.com/bios_jo_03152009.html |title=Jo Weldon| publisher= Sex Worker Arts Show|accessdate= March 30, 2013|archivedate=November 28, 2009|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091128090516/http://www.sexworkersartshow.com/bios_jo_03152009.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and co-produced ''W.O.(e).R.D., Women of experience Read Downtown'', a performance reading of literary works by undomesticated women.<ref>{{cite web|last= Ikard|first= Theresa|url=http://carnalnation.com/content/51279/5/jo-weldon |title=Burlesque's Jo Weldon on Feminism, Fluid Sexuality, Domestication Drag|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101120225134/http://carnalnation.com/content/51279/5/jo-weldon |archivedate=November 20, 2010|publisher=Carnal Nation|date=April 3, 2010|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Television and film appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" cellpadding=\"3\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"70\" | Year !! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" width=\"280\" | Appearance !! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" width=\"100\" | Role !! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" width=\"300\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1999 || Time Square Clean-Up || Herself || TV, Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1999\u20132006 || ''[[SexTV]]'' || Herself || TV series documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2005 || ''[[Leonard Cohen: I'm Your Man]]'' || Burlesque Beauty || Documentary, biography\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2006 || Monja satanica || Estudiante Amore || Short horror\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2006 || [[Josh Alan Friedman|''Tales of Times Square'']] || Anna Turner|| Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2006 || Alison Lapper/Spread Magazine/Lust Circus || Herself || TV, Documentary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2007 || [[What Not to Wear (U.S. TV series)|''What Not to Wear'']] || Herself || TV, Reality\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\